{
  "body": "Simple line-art illustration in the discipline of Japanese editorial book illustration. {{main_subject}}, with {{companion}}, in a quiet contemplative scene.\n\n— Background —\n{{background_elements}}\n\n— Line style —\n{{line_style}}. Lines are calm, confident, and refined — never sketchy-messy or rough unless the chosen line style specifies. Every line feels intentional. The whole image gives the feeling of being drawn slowly, with patience.\n\n— Color palette (CRITICAL — restrained palette discipline) —\n{{color_palette}}. The dominant visual language is monotone — most of the image lives in the dark/medium/light tones of the same neutral base. The accent color appears only on small, specific elements (e.g., one flower petal, one tiny accessory, one leaf, the cat's collar, a small fruit) — NEVER as a large fill. The accent is a whisper, not a statement.\n\n— Background paper —\n{{background_paper}}. The paper texture (if any) is extremely subtle, never overpowering the linework.\n\n— Fill treatment —\n{{fill_treatment}}. Where flat fills exist, they are absolutely flat — no gradients, no shading, no rendering. The image breathes through line and negative space, not through tonal modeling.\n\n— Composition —\n{{composition_layout}}. Captured in {{aspect_ratio}} aspect ratio. Generous negative space — at least 30–40% of the frame stays empty / breathing. The composition follows Japanese aesthetic principles of ma (間, the meaningful empty space) and wabi-sabi (quiet imperfection).\n\n— Mood —\nQuiet, calm, gently melancholic, contemplative, introspective. The kind of illustration that would appear inside a Muji catalog, a Brutus magazine column, a Kinfolk book chapter opening, or a contemporary Japanese poetry book. Not cute, not dramatic — just present and softly observant.\n\n— Style references —\nReference visual mood: contemporary Japanese illustrators like Yusuke Yamamoto, Mai Ide, Mai Igarashi; mid-century editorial line illustration; Korean linocut-influenced contemporary illustration. Premium book-publishing line-art aesthetic.\n\n— Additional details —\n{{extra_notes}}\n\n— Strictly avoid —\n- Do NOT use a wide colorful palette — keep the monotone discipline\n- Do NOT use the accent color as a large fill — it must be a small whisper accent only\n- Do NOT add gradients, shadows, or rendering — the work is flat and line-based\n- Do NOT add anime/manga big eyes, blush stickers, or chibi proportions — the figure has soft realistic proportions\n- Do NOT crowd the composition — preserve generous empty space (ma)\n- Do NOT add tone-rich realistic skin shading — skin and clothing are described by line, not by tone\n- Do NOT add photographic textures, brushy painterly strokes, or 3D rendering\n- Do NOT add modern UI elements (icons, buttons, frames)\n- Do NOT include text, watermarks, signatures, or logos (unless extra_notes specifies)\n- Do NOT make the line work shaky, broken, or chaotic — quiet confidence is the goal\n- Do NOT use bright cartoon colors even on the companion animal — the cat/dog/etc. stays in the monotone palette\n\nKeywords: line art, monoline, Japanese illustration, editorial, monotone, restrained palette, calm, quiet, ma, wabi-sabi, book illustration, contemporary minimalism, ink drawing",
